ss, which did not begin and simply end with the closure of the local mill in 2002. High examines the work-life histories of fifty paper mill workers and managers, as well as city officials, to gain an in-depth understanding of the impact of the formation and dissolution of a culture of industrialism. Oral history and memory are at the heart of One Job Town, challenging us to rethink the relationship between the past and the present in what was formerly known as the industrialized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeindustrializationzOntariozSturgeon Falls. 0aMills and mill-workzOntariozSturgeon Falls. 0aPaper industry workerszOntariozSturgeon Falls. 0aPaper millszOntariozSturgeon Falls. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aNorthern Ontario.  aSturgeon Falls.  adeindustrialization.  alabour.  amemory.  aoral history.  apaper.  apulp.  awork.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268622940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442686229.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles